\section*{Introduction}\label{sec:intro}
\nopagebreak[4]

The Pythagorean Theorem stands as one of the most fundamental and widely recognized results in all of mathematics. Named after the ancient Greek mathematician Pythagoras of Samos, who lived around 570--495 BCE, this theorem establishes a precise relationship between the three sides of any right triangle. The elegance and utility of this relationship have made it an indispensable tool across numerous fields, from architecture and engineering to navigation and computer graphics.

At its core, the Pythagorean Theorem provides a method for calculating unknown distances when certain measurements are known. This capability proves essential in countless practical situations: determining the length of a ladder needed to reach a specific height, calculating diagonal distances across rectangular spaces, verifying that corners form true right angles in construction projects, and establishing positions in coordinate systems. The theorem bridges the gap between geometric intuition and algebraic calculation, allowing precise numerical answers to spatial problems.

This chapter develops a thorough understanding of the Pythagorean Theorem and its applications. Students will learn to identify right triangles and their components, apply the theorem to find unknown side lengths, use the converse of the theorem to verify right angles, and solve real-world problems involving distance calculations. The learning objectives focus on understanding and solving worked examples that demonstrate these essential skills, preparing students for assessments and practical applications alike.

\needspace{6\baselineskip}
\section{The Pythagorean Theorem}\label{sec:theorem}
\nopagebreak[4]

\subsection{Fundamental Concepts}

Before stating the Pythagorean Theorem formally, it is essential to establish the terminology used when discussing right triangles. A \textbf{right triangle} is a triangle containing exactly one angle of $90°$, called the \textbf{right angle}. The two sides that form the right angle are called the \textbf{legs} of the triangle, while the side opposite the right angle is called the \textbf{hypotenuse}. The hypotenuse is always the longest side of a right triangle, a fact that follows directly from the geometric properties of triangles.

\begin{definitionbox}{Right Triangle Components}
In a right triangle:
\begin{itemize}[nosep]
\item The \textbf{legs} (often denoted $a$ and $b$) are the two sides that form the right angle.
\item The \textbf{hypotenuse} (often denoted $c$) is the side opposite the right angle.
\item The hypotenuse is always the longest side of the triangle.
\end{itemize}
\end{definitionbox}

\subsection{Statement of the Theorem}

The Pythagorean Theorem establishes a precise algebraic relationship between the lengths of the three sides of any right triangle. This relationship holds universally for all right triangles, regardless of their size or the specific measurements of their sides.

\begin{theorembox}{The Pythagorean Theorem}
In any right triangle with legs of length $a$ and $b$ and hypotenuse of length $c$:
\begin{equation}
a^2 + b^2 = c^2
\end{equation}
The sum of the squares of the lengths of the legs equals the square of the length of the hypotenuse.
\end{theorembox}

This theorem can be applied in two primary ways. When the lengths of both legs are known, the theorem allows calculation of the hypotenuse by rearranging to obtain $c = \sqrt{a^2 + b^2}$. Conversely, when the hypotenuse and one leg are known, the unknown leg can be found using $a = \sqrt{c^2 - b^2}$ or $b = \sqrt{c^2 - a^2}$.

