\subsection{Pythagorean Triples}

Certain combinations of positive integers satisfy the Pythagorean equation exactly. These special sets of three integers $(a, b, c)$ where $a^2 + b^2 = c^2$ are called \textbf{Pythagorean triples}. The most famous example is $(3, 4, 5)$, which appears frequently in practical applications and educational contexts.

\begin{table}[H]
\centering
\begin{tabular}{@{}cccl@{}}
\toprule
$a$ & $b$ & $c$ & Verification \\
\midrule
3 & 4 & 5 & $9 + 16 = 25$ \\
5 & 12 & 13 & $25 + 144 = 169$ \\
8 & 15 & 17 & $64 + 225 = 289$ \\
7 & 24 & 25 & $49 + 576 = 625$ \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\caption{Common Pythagorean triples and their verification.}
\end{table}

Any multiple of a Pythagorean triple is also a Pythagorean triple. For instance, multiplying $(3, 4, 5)$ by 2 yields $(6, 8, 10)$, and multiplying by 10 yields $(30, 40, 50)$. This scaling property proves useful when working with larger measurements in practical applications.

\needspace{6\baselineskip}
\section{Applications of the Theorem}\label{sec:applications}
\nopagebreak[4]

\subsection{Finding Unknown Side Lengths}

The most direct application of the Pythagorean Theorem involves calculating an unknown side of a right triangle when two sides are known. The procedure depends on whether the unknown side is the hypotenuse or one of the legs.

\textbf{Finding the hypotenuse:} When both legs $a$ and $b$ are known, the hypotenuse is calculated as:
\begin{equation}
c = \sqrt{a^2 + b^2}
\end{equation}

\textbf{Finding a leg:} When the hypotenuse $c$ and one leg are known, the other leg is calculated as:
\begin{align}
a &= \sqrt{c^2 - b^2} \\
b &= \sqrt{c^2 - a^2}
\end{align}

It is crucial to remember that the hypotenuse must always be the longest side. When solving for a leg, the expression under the square root must be positive, which serves as a useful check on the problem setup.

\subsection{Real-World Applications}

The Pythagorean Theorem finds extensive use in practical situations where right angles occur naturally or by design. Construction workers use the theorem to verify that walls meet at right angles, a technique sometimes called the ``3-4-5 method.'' By measuring 3 units along one wall, 4 units along the adjacent wall, and checking that the diagonal measures exactly 5 units, workers can confirm a perfect right angle.

Navigation and surveying rely heavily on the theorem for calculating distances. When direct measurement is impractical, surveyors can establish right triangles and use known measurements to compute unknown distances. Similarly, pilots and sailors use the theorem in conjunction with coordinate systems to determine positions and plot courses.

In architecture and engineering, the theorem helps determine structural dimensions, calculate material requirements, and ensure proper fit of components. The diagonal bracing in buildings, the pitch of roofs, and the layout of floor plans all involve applications of this fundamental relationship.

\needspace{6\baselineskip}
\section{The Converse of the Pythagorean Theorem}\label{sec:converse}
\nopagebreak[4]

The Pythagorean Theorem has a converse that proves equally useful in applications. While the theorem states that right triangles satisfy the equation $a^2 + b^2 = c^2$, the converse states that any triangle satisfying this equation must be a right triangle.

\begin{theorembox}{Converse of the Pythagorean Theorem}
If a triangle has sides of length $a$, $b$, and $c$ where $c$ is the longest side, and if $a^2 + b^2 = c^2$, then the triangle is a right triangle with the right angle opposite side $c$.
\end{theorembox}

This converse provides a powerful method for verifying whether a given triangle is a right triangle. The procedure involves three steps: first, identify the longest side as the candidate for the hypotenuse; second, calculate the sum of squares of the two shorter sides; third, compare this sum to the square of the longest side. If equality holds, the triangle is a right triangle.

The converse also extends to identify acute and obtuse triangles. If $a^2 + b^2 > c^2$, the triangle is acute (all angles less than $90°$). If $a^2 + b^2 < c^2$, the triangle is obtuse (one angle greater than $90°$). This classification proves valuable in geometric analysis and construction verification.

